  "prompt": "Why is a body heavier after a person dies?",
  "response": "A body does not actually become heavier after a person dies. The weight of the body remains the same immediately after death because the body\u2019s mass does not change. However, there are a few phenomena that might lead to the perception or temporary effects related to weight:\n\n1. **Rigor Mortis**: After death, muscles stiffen due to chemical changes (rigor mortis). This stiffness might make the body feel more rigid and difficult to lift, potentially giving the impression of increased weight, though the actual weight hasn\u2019t changed.\n\n2. **Fluid Accumulation**: In some cases, fluids might accumulate in certain areas of the body due to gravity and the cessation of circulation, which could make the body feel denser or heavier in specific regions.\n\n3. **Decomposition**: Over time, as decomposition begins, gases produced by bacteria can cause the body to bloat. This bloating might make the body appear larger, but it does not increase its weight. In fact, as decomposition progresses, the body loses mass through the release of gases and fluids.\n\nTherefore, the idea that a body becomes heavier after death is a misconception. Any perceived change is due to physical or chemical changes in the body, not an actual increase in weight.",
